description: From Middle English up, from Old English upp, from Proto-Germanic *upp, see more there.

entries.meaning: Facing upwards.
examples: Turn the cloth over so that the patterned side is up.

entries.meaning: On or at a physically higher level.
examples: The flood waters are up again across large areas of the country.

entries.meaning: Headed or designated to go upward (as an escalator, stairway, elevator etc.) or toward (as a run-up).
examples: Where is the up escalator?

entries.meaning: Fitted or fixed at a high or relatively high position, especially on a wall or ceiling.
examples: All the notices are up now.
The Christmas decorations are up.

entries.meaning: (by extension) Available to view or use; made public; posted.
examples: Is your new video up yet? I looked on the website, but I couldn't find it.

entries.meaning: Aloft.
examples: The kite is up!

entries.meaning: Raised; lifted.
examples: The castle drawbridge was up.
Don't go into the living room just now – I've got the carpet up.

entries.meaning: Built, constructed.
examples: Are the new buildings up yet?

entries.meaning: Standing; upright.
examples: The audience were up and on their feet.

entries.meaning: (obsolete) Risen up, rebelling, in revolt.
Awake and out of bed.
examples: I can’t believe it’s 3 a.m. and you’re still up.

entries.meaning: (horse-racing) Riding the horse; mounted.
(of the sun or moon) Above the horizon, in the sky.
examples: It'll get warmer once the sun's up.

entries.meaning: Larger; greater in quantity, volume, value etc.
examples: Sales are up compared to last quarter.
My temperature is up this morning.

entries.meaning: Indicating a larger or higher quantity.
examples: The barometer is up, so fine weather should be on the way.

entries.meaning: Ahead; leading; winning.
examples: The home team were up by two goals at half-time.

entries.meaning: Finished, to an end
examples: Time is up!
Her contract is up next month, so it's time to negotiate another one.

entries.meaning: In a good mood.
examples: I’m feeling up today.

entries.meaning: (usually in the phrase up for) Willing; ready.
examples: If you are up for a trip, let’s go.

entries.meaning: Next in a sequence.
examples: Smith is up to bat.

entries.meaning: (not used attributively) Happening; new; of concern. See also what's up, what's up with.
examples: What's up, bro?
What is up with that project at headquarters?
When I saw his face, I knew something was up.

entries.meaning: (poker, postnominal) Said of the higher-ranking pair in a two pair.
examples: AAKK = aces up
QQ33 = queens up

entries.meaning: Well-informed; current.
examples: I’m not up on the latest news. What’s going on?

entries.meaning: (computing) Functional; working.
examples: Is the server back up?

entries.meaning: (of a railway line or train) Traveling towards a major terminus.
examples: The London train is on the up line.

entries.meaning: (US, bartending) Chilled and served without ice.
examples: Would you like that drink up or on ice?

entries.meaning: (slang) Erect.
(UK) At university (especially Oxford or Cambridge).
examples: When I was up (1965–68) I had a group of idle friends who occupied their time and mine betting on horses, getting drunk and sprawling about telling creepy tales.

entries.meaning: (slang, graffiti) well-known; renowned
examples: Being "up" means having numerous graffiti in the tagging landscape.

entries.meaning: Away from the surface of the Earth or other planet; in opposite direction to the downward pull of gravity.
examples: I looked up and saw the airplane overhead.

entries.meaning: To or at a physically higher or more elevated position.
examples: All day we climbed up and up.

entries.meaning: To a higher level of some quantity or notional quantity, such as price, volume, pitch, happiness, etc.
examples: Gold has gone up with the uncertainty in the world markets.
Turn it up, I can barely hear it.
Listen to your voice go up at the end of a question.
Cheer up, the weekend's almost here.

entries.meaning: To or in a position of equal advance or equality; not short of, back of, less advanced than, away from, etc.; usually followed by to or with.
examples: I was up to my chin in water.
A stranger came up and asked me for directions.

entries.meaning: (intensifier) Used as an aspect marker to indicate a completed action or state; thoroughly, completely.
examples: I will mix up the puzzle pieces.
Tear up the contract.
He really messed up.
Please type up our monthly report.
Drink up. The pub is closing.
Can you sum up your research?
The meteor burned up in the atmosphere.
I need to sew up the hole in this shirt.

entries.meaning: To or from one's possession or consideration.
examples: I picked up some milk on the way home.
The committee will take up your request.
She had to give up her driver's license after the accident.

entries.meaning: North.
examples: I live in Florida, but I'm going up to New York to visit my family this weekend.

entries.meaning: Towards or at a central place, or any place that is visualised as 'up' by virtue of local features or local convention, or arbitrarily, irrespective of direction or elevation change.
examples: We travelled from Yorkshire up to London.
I'm going up to the other end of town.
He lives up by the railway station.

entries.meaning: (rail transport) Towards the principal terminus, towards milepost zero.
Aside or away, so as no longer to be present or in use.
examples: to lay up riches; put up your weapons

entries.meaning: (sailing) Against the wind or current.
(Cartesian graph) In a positive vertical direction.
(cricket) Relatively close to the batsman.
examples: The bowler pitched the ball up.

entries.meaning: (US, bartending) Without additional ice.
examples: A Cosmopolitan is typically served up.

entries.meaning: (UK, academia, dated) To university, especially to Cambridge or Oxford.
examples: She's going up to read Classics this September.

entries.meaning: (uncountable) The direction opposed to the pull of gravity.
examples: Up is a good way to go.

entries.meaning: (countable) A positive thing, or a time or situation when things are going well.
examples: I hate almost everything about my job. The only up is that it's so close to home.
There are many ups to caravanning, but also many downs.
I've been on an up all this week.

entries.meaning: (particle physics) An up quark.
examples: Hypernym: flavor

entries.meaning: An upstairs room of a two story house.
examples: She lives in a two-up two-down.

entries.meaning: Toward the top of.
examples: The cat climbed up the tree.
They walk up the steps.

entries.meaning: Toward the center, source, or main point of reference; toward the end at which something is attached.
examples: The information made its way up the chain of command to the general.
I felt something crawling up my arm.

entries.meaning: From south to north of.
examples: We sailed up the East Coast of England from Ipswich to South Shields.

entries.meaning: Further along (in any direction).
examples: Go up the street until you see the sign.

entries.meaning: From the mouth towards the source of (a river or waterway).
examples: He led an expedition up the Amazon.

entries.meaning: (vulgar slang) Of a man: having sex with.
examples: Phwoar, look at that bird. I'd love to be up her.

entries.meaning: (colloquial) At (a given place, especially one imagined to be higher or more distant from a central location).
examples: I'll see you later up the snooker club.

verbs.description: up (third-person singular simple present ups, present participle upping, simple past and past participle upped)

entries.meaning: (transitive, poetic or in certain phrases) To physically raise or lift.
examples: We upped anchor and sailed away.

entries.meaning: (transitive, colloquial) To increase the level or amount of.
examples: If we up the volume, we may be able to hear what he says.
As usual, they've upped the prices for Valentine's Day.

entries.meaning: (transitive, colloquial) To promote.
examples: It wasn’t long before they upped him to Vice President.

entries.meaning: (intransitive, often in combination with another verb) To rise to a standing position; hence, by extension, to act suddenly; see also up and.
examples: She was sitting there quietly, then all of a sudden she upped and left.
He just upped and quit.
He upped and punched that guy.

entries.meaning: (intransitive, archaic or poetic) To ascend; to climb up.
examples: "Will ye up, lass, and ride behind me?".

entries.meaning: (computing, slang, transitive) To upload.
examples: 100 new apps and games have just been upped.
